UNOFFICIAL COPY 26 RS BR 1019
1 AN ACT relating to proactive postsecondary admission.
2 Be it enacted by the General Assembly of the Commonwealth of Kentucky:
3 SECTION 1. A NEW SECTION OF KRS CHAPTER 164 IS CREATED TO
4 READ AS FOLLOWS:
5 (1) As used in this section:
6 (a) "Certified nonpublic school" means a private, parochial, or church school
7 that is certified by the Kentucky Board of Education pursuant to KRS
8 156.160(2);
9 (b) "Council" means the Council on Postsecondary Education; and
10 (c) "Eligible high school student" means a high school student in his or her
11 final year of enrollment at a Kentucky public high school or certified
12 nonpublic high school that:
13 1. Meets or exceeds the minimum academic qualification for prospective
14 admission to a public postsecondary education institution established
15 pursuant to subsection (3)(a) of this section; and
16 2. Qualifies as a Kentucky resident, as determined by the council.
17 (2) There is hereby established a proactive postsecondary admissions program to be
18 managed by the council for the purpose of:
19 (a) Notifying each eligible high school student of his or her eligibility for
20 prospective admission to a public postsecondary education institution; and
21 (b) Providing instructions to each eligible high school student on how to access
22 the common online application to apply for full admission to public
23 postsecondary education institutions in Kentucky.
24 (3) No later than July 1, 2027, each public postsecondary education institution shall:
25 (a) Establish a minimum academic qualification for prospective admission to
26 the institution through the proactive postsecondary admissions program
27 that exclusively includes:
Page 1 of 13
XXXX 1/8/2026 8:52 AM Jacketed

UNOFFICIAL COPY 26 RS BR 1019
1 1. A minimum grade point average; or
2 2. A combination of a minimum grade point average and minimum score
3 on a nationally recognized college readiness examination approved by
4 the council for the purposes of this section; and
5 (b) Implement the common online application approved by the council
6 pursuant to Section 2 of this Act for the purpose of evaluating the admission
7 of full-time, first-year students. The common application shall require an
8 applicant to submit proof that he or she meets the minimum academic
9 qualification for prospective admission at an institution established
10 pursuant to paragraph (a) of this subsection. An institution may request
11 additional application information or materials outside of the common
12 application. The council may establish additional requirements for the
13 approval of a common application.
14 (4) (a) On or before September 1 of each year, the Kentucky Department of
15 Education and each certified nonpublic school shall submit to the council
16 and the Kentucky Center for Statistics a compiled list of all high school
17 students who most recently completed their junior year, including each
18 student’s name, enrolled school district or certified nonpublic school, school
19 identification number, Social Security number, address, cumulative
20 unweighted grade point average, and highest score on a nationally
21 recognized college readiness examination approved by the council that is in
22 the possession of the department or certified nonpublic school.
23 (b) On or before September 1 of each year, the Kentucky Higher Education
24 Assistance Authority shall submit to the council the Kentucky Educational
25 Excellence Scholarship award amounts of public and certified nonpublic
26 high school students who were reported to the authority under KRS
27 164.7885 and most recently completed their junior year in a manner agreed
Page 2 of 13
XXXX 1/8/2026 8:52 AM Jacketed

UNOFFICIAL COPY 26 RS BR 1019
1 upon by the council and the authority.
2 (5) (a) Beginning in 2028, the council shall utilize data collected pursuant to
3 subsection (4) of this section to send a personalized prospective admissions
4 letter to each eligible high school student that:
5 1. Notifies the recipient student of each public postsecondary education
6 institution in Kentucky where the recipient student qualifies for
7 prospective admission;
8 2. Provides instructions for the recipient student to access the common
9 online application to apply for full admission to public postsecondary
10 education institutions; and
11 3. Provides the recipient student’s Kentucky Educational Excellence
12 Scholarship award amount, if the recipient is eligible for the
13 scholarship.
14 (b) A personalized prospective admission letter sent pursuant to paragraph (a)
15 of this subsection shall not constitute an offer or guarantee of admission to
16 any public postsecondary institution identified in the letter.
17 (6) Each public postsecondary education institution shall retain the right to perform
18 a comprehensive review of all admissions applications internally. An institution
19 shall not be required to grant acceptance or priority consideration to any student
20 that applies to the institution, regardless of whether:
21 (a) The application was submitted through the proactive postsecondary
22 admissions program established by this section; or
23 (b) An applicant meets or exceeds the minimum qualification for prospective
24 admission to the institution established pursuant to subsection (3)(a) of this
25 section.
26 SECTION 2. A NEW SECTION OF KRS CHAPTER 151B IS CREATED TO
27 READ AS FOLLOWS:
Page 3 of 13
XXXX 1/8/2026 8:52 AM Jacketed

UNOFFICIAL COPY 26 RS BR 1019
1 The Kentucky Center for Statistics, in collaboration with the Kentucky Department of
2 Education and the Council on Postsecondary Education, shall annually publish data
3 on academic and workforce outcomes of each cohort reported to the center in
4 accordance with Section 1 of this Act, including the cohort's college going rates,
5 postsecondary credential attainment, and employment and wage outcomes.
6 Section 3. KRS 164.020 is amended to read as follows:
7 The Council on Postsecondary Education in Kentucky shall:
8 (1) Develop and implement the strategic agenda with the advice and counsel of the
9 Strategic Committee on Postsecondary Education. The council shall provide for and
10 direct the planning process and subsequent strategic implementation plans based on
11 the strategic agenda as provided in KRS 164.0203;
12 (2) Revise the strategic agenda and strategic implementation plan with the advice and
13 counsel of the committee as set forth in KRS 164.004;
14 (3) Develop a system of public accountability related to the strategic agenda by
15 evaluating the performance and effectiveness of the state's postsecondary system.
16 The council shall prepare a report in conjunction with the accountability reporting
17 described in KRS 164.095, which shall be submitted to the committee, the
18 Governor, and the General Assembly by December 1 annually. This report shall
19 include a description of contributions by postsecondary institutions to the quality of
20 elementary and secondary education in the Commonwealth;
21 (4) Review, revise, and approve the missions of the state's universities and the
22 Kentucky Community and Technical College System. The Council on
23 Postsecondary Education shall have the final authority to determine the compliance
24 of postsecondary institutions with their academic, service, and research missions;
25 (5) Establish and ensure that all postsecondary institutions in Kentucky cooperatively
26 provide for an integrated system of postsecondary education. The council shall
27 guard against inappropriate and unnecessary conflict and duplication by promoting
Page 4 of 13
XXXX 1/8/2026 8:52 AM Jacketed

UNOFFICIAL COPY 26 RS BR 1019
1 transferability of credits and easy access of information among institutions;
2 (6) Engage in analyses and research to determine the overall needs of postsecondary
3 education and adult education in the Commonwealth;
4 (7) Develop plans that may be required by federal legislation. The council shall for all
5 purposes of federal legislation relating to planning be considered the "single state
6 agency" as that term may be used in federal legislation. When federal legislation
7 requires additional representation on any "single state agency," the Council on
8 Postsecondary Education shall establish advisory groups necessary to satisfy federal
9 legislative or regulatory guidelines;
10 (8) (a) Determine tuition and approve the minimum qualifications for admission to
11 the state postsecondary educational system. In defining residency, the council
12 shall classify a student as having Kentucky residency if the student met the
13 residency requirements at the beginning of his or her last year in high school
14 and enters a Kentucky postsecondary education institution within two (2)
15 years of high school graduation. In determining the tuition for non-Kentucky
16 residents, the council shall consider the fees required of Kentucky students by
17 institutions in adjoining states, the resident fees charged by other states, the
18 total actual per student cost of training in the institutions for which the fees
19 are being determined, and the ratios of Kentucky students to non-Kentucky
20 students comprising the enrollments of the respective institutions, and other
21 factors the council may in its sole discretion deem pertinent, except that the
22 Kentucky Community and Technical College System may assess a mandatory
23 student fee not to exceed eight dollars ($8) per credit hour to be used
24 exclusively for debt service on amounts not to exceed seventy-five percent
25 (75%) of the total projects cost of the Kentucky Community and Technical
26 College System agency bond projects included in 2014 Ky. Acts ch. 117, Part
27 II, J., 11.
